27#ifndef _I915_REG_H_
28#define _I915_REG_H_
29
30#define _PIPE(pipe, a, b) ((a) + (pipe)*((b)-(a)))
31#define _PLANE(plane, a, b) _PIPE(plane, a, b)
32#define _TRANSCODER(tran, a, b) ((a) + (tran)*((b)-(a)))
33#define _PORT(port, a, b) ((a) + (port)*((b)-(a)))
34#define _PIPE3(pipe, a, b, c) ((pipe) == PIPE_A ? (a) : \
35 (pipe) == PIPE_B ? (b) : (c))
36#define _PORT3(port, a, b, c) ((port) == PORT_A ? (a) : \
37 (port) == PORT_B ? (b) : (c))
38
39#define _MASKED_FIELD(mask, value) ({ \
40 if (__builtin_constant_p(mask)) { \
41 BUILD_BUG_ON_MSG(((mask) & 0xffff0000), "Incorrect mask"); \
42 } \
43 if (__builtin_constant_p(value)) { \
44 BUILD_BUG_ON_MSG((value) & 0xffff0000, "Incorrect value"); \
45 } \
46 if (__builtin_constant_p(mask) && __builtin_constant_p(value)) { \
47 BUILD_BUG_ON_MSG((value) & ~(mask), \
48 "Incorrect value for mask"); \
49 } \
50 (mask) << 16 | (value); })
51#define _MASKED_BIT_ENABLE(a) ({ typeof(a) _a = (a); _MASKED_FIELD(_a, _a); })
52#define _MASKED_BIT_DISABLE(a) (_MASKED_FIELD((a), 0))
53

79#define GC_DISPLAY_CLOCK_167_MHZ_PNV (7 << 4)

83#define GM45_GC_RENDER_CLOCK_320_MHZ (9 << 0)
84#define GM45_GC_RENDER_CLOCK_400_MHZ (0xb << 0)

259/*
260 * Memory interface instructions used by the kernel
261 */
262#define MI_INSTR(opcode, flags) (((opcode) << 23) | (flags))
263/* Many MI commands use bit 22 of the header dword for GGTT vs PPGTT */
264#define MI_GLOBAL_GTT (1<<22)
265
266#define MI_NOOP MI_INSTR(0, 0)
267#define MI_USER_INTERRUPT MI_INSTR(0x02, 0)
268#define MI_WAIT_FOR_EVENT MI_INSTR(0x03, 0)
269#define MI_WAIT_FOR_OVERLAY_FLIP (1<<16)
270#define MI_WAIT_FOR_PLANE_B_FLIP (1<<6)
271#define MI_WAIT_FOR_PLANE_A_FLIP (1<<2)
272#define MI_WAIT_FOR_PLANE_A_SCANLINES (1<<1)
273#define MI_FLUSH MI_INSTR(0x04, 0)
274#define MI_READ_FLUSH (1 << 0)
275#define MI_EXE_FLUSH (1 << 1)
276#define MI_NO_WRITE_FLUSH (1 << 2)
277#define MI_SCENE_COUNT (1 << 3) /* just increment scene count */
278#define MI_END_SCENE (1 << 4) /* flush binner and incr scene count */
279#define MI_INVALIDATE_ISP (1 << 5) /* invalidate indirect state pointers */
280#define MI_REPORT_HEAD MI_INSTR(0x07, 0)
281#define MI_ARB_ON_OFF MI_INSTR(0x08, 0)
282#define MI_ARB_ENABLE (1<<0)
283#define MI_ARB_DISABLE (0<<0)
284#define MI_BATCH_BUFFER_END MI_INSTR(0x0a, 0)
285#define MI_SUSPEND_FLUSH MI_INSTR(0x0b, 0)
286#define MI_SUSPEND_FLUSH_EN (1<<0)
287#define MI_SET_APPID MI_INSTR(0x0e, 0)
288#define MI_OVERLAY_FLIP MI_INSTR(0x11, 0)
289#define MI_OVERLAY_CONTINUE (0x0<<21)
290#define MI_OVERLAY_ON (0x1<<21)
291#define MI_OVERLAY_OFF (0x2<<21)
292#define MI_LOAD_SCAN_LINES_INCL MI_INSTR(0x12, 0)
293#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP MI_INSTR(0x14, 2)
294#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_I915 MI_INSTR(0x14, 1)
295#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_PLANE(n) ((n) << 20)
296/* IVB has funny definitions for which plane to flip. */
297#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_IVB_PLANE_A (0 << 19)
298#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_IVB_PLANE_B (1 << 19)
299#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_IVB_SPRITE_A (2 << 19)
300#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_IVB_SPRITE_B (3 << 19)
301#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_IVB_PLANE_C (4 << 19)
302#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_IVB_SPRITE_C (5 << 19)
303/* SKL ones */
304#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_1_A (0 << 8)
305#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_1_B (1 << 8)
306#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_1_C (2 << 8)
307#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_2_A (4 << 8)
308#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_2_B (5 << 8)
309#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_2_C (6 << 8)
310#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_3_A (7 << 8)
311#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_3_B (8 << 8)
312#define MI_DISPLAY_FLIP_SKL_PLANE_3_C (9 << 8)
313#define MI_SEMAPHORE_MBOX MI_INSTR(0x16, 1) /* gen6, gen7 */
314#define MI_SEMAPHORE_GLOBAL_GTT (1<<22)
315#define MI_SEMAPHORE_UPDATE (1<<21)
316#define MI_SEMAPHORE_COMPARE (1<<20)
317#define MI_SEMAPHORE_REGISTER (1<<18)
318#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_VR (0<<16) /* RCS wait for VCS (RVSYNC) */
319#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_VER (1<<16) /* RCS wait for VECS (RVESYNC) */
320#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_BR (2<<16) /* RCS wait for BCS (RBSYNC) */
321#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_BV (0<<16) /* VCS wait for BCS (VBSYNC) */
322#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_VEV (1<<16) /* VCS wait for VECS (VVESYNC) */
323#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_RV (2<<16) /* VCS wait for RCS (VRSYNC) */
324#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_RB (0<<16) /* BCS wait for RCS (BRSYNC) */
325#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_VEB (1<<16) /* BCS wait for VECS (BVESYNC) */
326#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_VB (2<<16) /* BCS wait for VCS (BVSYNC) */
327#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_BVE (0<<16) /* VECS wait for BCS (VEBSYNC) */
328#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_VVE (1<<16) /* VECS wait for VCS (VEVSYNC) */
329#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_RVE (2<<16) /* VECS wait for RCS (VERSYNC) */
330#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_INVALID (3<<16)
331#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SYNC_MASK (3<<16)
332#define MI_SET_CONTEXT MI_INSTR(0x18, 0)
333#define MI_MM_SPACE_GTT (1<<8)
334#define MI_MM_SPACE_PHYSICAL (0<<8)
335#define MI_SAVE_EXT_STATE_EN (1<<3)
336#define MI_RESTORE_EXT_STATE_EN (1<<2)
337#define MI_FORCE_RESTORE (1<<1)
338#define MI_RESTORE_INHIBIT (1<<0)
339#define HSW_MI_RS_SAVE_STATE_EN (1<<3)
340#define HSW_MI_RS_RESTORE_STATE_EN (1<<2)
341#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SIGNAL MI_INSTR(0x1b, 0) /* GEN8+ */
342#define MI_SEMAPHORE_TARGET(engine) ((engine)<<15)
343#define MI_SEMAPHORE_WAIT MI_INSTR(0x1c, 2) /* GEN8+ */
344#define MI_SEMAPHORE_POLL (1<<15)
345#define MI_SEMAPHORE_SAD_GTE_SDD (1<<12)
346#define MI_STORE_DWORD_IMM MI_INSTR(0x20, 1)
347#define MI_STORE_DWORD_IMM_GEN4 MI_INSTR(0x20, 2)
348#define MI_MEM_VIRTUAL (1 << 22) /* 945,g33,965 */
349#define MI_USE_GGTT (1 << 22) /* g4x+ */
350#define MI_STORE_DWORD_INDEX MI_INSTR(0x21, 1)
351#define MI_STORE_DWORD_INDEX_SHIFT 2
352/* Official intel docs are somewhat sloppy concerning MI_LOAD_REGISTER_IMM:
353 * - Always issue a MI_NOOP _before_ the MI_LOAD_REGISTER_IMM - otherwise hw
354 * simply ignores the register load under certain conditions.
355 * - One can actually load arbitrary many arbitrary registers: Simply issue x
356 * address/value pairs. Don't overdue it, though, x <= 2^4 must hold!
357 */
358#define MI_LOAD_REGISTER_IMM(x) MI_INSTR(0x22, 2*(x)-1)
359#define MI_LRI_FORCE_POSTED (1<<12)
360#define MI_STORE_REGISTER_MEM MI_INSTR(0x24, 1)
361#define MI_STORE_REGISTER_MEM_GEN8 MI_INSTR(0x24, 2)
362#define MI_SRM_LRM_GLOBAL_GTT (1<<22)
363#define MI_FLUSH_DW MI_INSTR(0x26, 1) /* for GEN6 */
364#define MI_FLUSH_DW_STORE_INDEX (1<<21)
365#define MI_INVALIDATE_TLB (1<<18)
366#define MI_FLUSH_DW_OP_STOREDW (1<<14)
367#define MI_FLUSH_DW_OP_MASK (3<<14)
368#define MI_FLUSH_DW_NOTIFY (1<<8)
369#define MI_INVALIDATE_BSD (1<<7)
370#define MI_FLUSH_DW_USE_GTT (1<<2)
371#define MI_FLUSH_DW_USE_PPGTT (0<<2)
372#define MI_LOAD_REGISTER_MEM MI_INSTR(0x29, 1)
373#define MI_LOAD_REGISTER_MEM_GEN8 MI_INSTR(0x29, 2)
374#define MI_BATCH_BUFFER MI_INSTR(0x30, 1)
375#define MI_BATCH_NON_SECURE (1)
376/* for snb/ivb/vlv this also means "batch in ppgtt" when ppgtt is enabled. */
377#define MI_BATCH_NON_SECURE_I965 (1<<8)
378#define MI_BATCH_PPGTT_HSW (1<<8)
379#define MI_BATCH_NON_SECURE_HSW (1<<13)
380#define MI_BATCH_BUFFER_START MI_INSTR(0x31, 0)
381#define MI_BATCH_GTT (2<<6) /* aliased with (1<<7) on gen4 */
382#define MI_BATCH_BUFFER_START_GEN8 MI_INSTR(0x31, 1)
383#define MI_BATCH_RESOURCE_STREAMER (1<<10)
384
385#define MI_PREDICATE_SRC0 (0x2400)
386#define MI_PREDICATE_SRC1 (0x2408)
387
388#define MI_PREDICATE_RESULT_2 (0x2214)
389#define LOWER_SLICE_ENABLED (1<<0)
390#define LOWER_SLICE_DISABLED (0<<0)

392/*
393 * 3D instructions used by the kernel
394 */
395#define GFX_INSTR(opcode, flags) ((0x3 << 29) | ((opcode) << 24) | (flags))
396
397#define GFX_OP_RASTER_RULES ((0x3<<29)|(0x7<<24))
398#define GFX_OP_SCISSOR ((0x3<<29)|(0x1c<<24)|(0x10<<19))
399#define SC_UPDATE_SCISSOR (0x1<<1)
400#define SC_ENABLE_MASK (0x1<<0)
401#define SC_ENABLE (0x1<<0)
402#define GFX_OP_LOAD_INDIRECT ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x7<<16))
403#define GFX_OP_SCISSOR_INFO ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x81<<16)|(0x1))
404#define SCI_YMIN_MASK (0xffff<<16)
405#define SCI_XMIN_MASK (0xffff<<0)
406#define SCI_YMAX_MASK (0xffff<<16)
407#define SCI_XMAX_MASK (0xffff<<0)
408#define GFX_OP_SCISSOR_ENABLE ((0x3<<29)|(0x1c<<24)|(0x10<<19))
409#define GFX_OP_SCISSOR_RECT ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x81<<16)|1)
410#define GFX_OP_COLOR_FACTOR ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x1<<16)|0x0)
411#define GFX_OP_STIPPLE ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x83<<16))
412#define GFX_OP_MAP_INFO ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|0x4)
413#define GFX_OP_DESTBUFFER_VARS ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x85<<16)|0x0)
414#define GFX_OP_DESTBUFFER_INFO ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x8e<<16)|1)
415#define GFX_OP_DRAWRECT_INFO ((0x3<<29)|(0x1d<<24)|(0x80<<16)|(0x3))

748/**
749 * DOC: DPIO
750 *
751 * VLV, CHV and BXT have slightly peculiar display PHYs for driving DP/HDMI
752 * ports. DPIO is the name given to such a display PHY. These PHYs
753 * don't follow the standard programming model using direct MMIO
754 * registers, and instead their registers must be accessed trough IOSF
755 * sideband. VLV has one such PHY for driving ports B and C, and CHV
756 * adds another PHY for driving port D. Each PHY responds to specific
757 * IOSF-SB port.
758 *
759 * Each display PHY is made up of one or two channels. Each channel
760 * houses a common lane part which contains the PLL and other common
761 * logic. CH0 common lane also contains the IOSF-SB logic for the
762 * Common Register Interface (CRI) ie. the DPIO registers. CRI clock
763 * must be running when any DPIO registers are accessed.
764 *
765 * In addition to having their own registers, the PHYs are also
766 * controlled through some dedicated signals from the display
767 * controller. These include PLL reference clock enable, PLL enable,
768 * and CRI clock selection, for example.
769 *
770 * Eeach channel also has two splines (also called data lanes), and
771 * each spline is made up of one Physical Access Coding Sub-Layer
772 * (PCS) block and two TX lanes. So each channel has two PCS blocks
773 * and four TX lanes. The TX lanes are used as DP lanes or TMDS
774 * data/clock pairs depending on the output type.
775 *
776 * Additionally the PHY also contains an AUX lane with AUX blocks
777 * for each channel. This is used for DP AUX communication, but
778 * this fact isn't really relevant for the driver since AUX is
779 * controlled from the display controller side. No DPIO registers
780 * need to be accessed during AUX communication,
781 *
782 * Generally on VLV/CHV the common lane corresponds to the pipe and
783 * the spline (PCS/TX) corresponds to the port.
784 *
785 * For dual channel PHY (VLV/CHV):
786 *
787 * pipe A == CMN/PLL/REF CH0
788 *
789 * pipe B == CMN/PLL/REF CH1
790 *
791 * port B == PCS/TX CH0
792 *
793 * port C == PCS/TX CH1
794 *
795 * This is especially important when we cross the streams
796 * ie. drive port B with pipe B, or port C with pipe A.
797 *
798 * For single channel PHY (CHV):
799 *
800 * pipe C == CMN/PLL/REF CH0
801 *
802 * port D == PCS/TX CH0
803 *
804 * On BXT the entire PHY channel corresponds to the port. That means
805 * the PLL is also now associated with the port rather than the pipe,
806 * and so the clock needs to be routed to the appropriate transcoder.
807 * Port A PLL is directly connected to transcoder EDP and port B/C
808 * PLLs can be routed to any transcoder A/B/C.
809 *
810 * Note: DDI0 is digital port B, DD1 is digital port C, and DDI2 is
811 * digital port D (CHV) or port A (BXT).
812 */
813/*
814 * Dual channel PHY (VLV/CHV/BXT)
815 * ---------------------------------
816 * | CH0 | CH1 |
817 * | CMN/PLL/REF | CMN/PLL/REF |
818 * |---------------|---------------| Display PHY
819 * | PCS01 | PCS23 | PCS01 | PCS23 |
820 * |-------|-------|-------|-------|
821 * |TX0|TX1|TX2|TX3|TX0|TX1|TX2|TX3|
822 * ---------------------------------
823 * | DDI0 | DDI1 | DP/HDMI ports
824 * ---------------------------------
825 *
826 * Single channel PHY (CHV/BXT)
827 * -----------------
828 * | CH0 |
829 * | CMN/PLL/REF |
830 * |---------------| Display PHY
831 * | PCS01 | PCS23 |
832 * |-------|-------|
833 * |TX0|TX1|TX2|TX3|
834 * -----------------
835 * | DDI2 | DP/HDMI port
836 * -----------------
837 */
838#define DPIO_DEVFN 0
839
840#define DPIO_CTL (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x2110)
841#define DPIO_MODSEL1 (1<<3) /* if ref clk b == 27 */
842#define DPIO_MODSEL0 (1<<2) /* if ref clk a == 27 */
843#define DPIO_SFR_BYPASS (1<<1)
844#define DPIO_CMNRST (1<<0)
845
846#define DPIO_PHY(pipe) ((pipe) >> 1)
847#define DPIO_PHY_IOSF_PORT(phy) (dev_priv->dpio_phy_iosf_port[phy])
848
849/*
850 * Per pipe/PLL DPIO regs
851 */
852#define _VLV_PLL_DW3_CH0 0x800c
853#define DPIO_POST_DIV_SHIFT (28) /* 3 bits */
854#define DPIO_POST_DIV_DAC 0
855#define DPIO_POST_DIV_HDMIDP 1 /* DAC 225-400M rate */
856#define DPIO_POST_DIV_LVDS1 2
857#define DPIO_POST_DIV_LVDS2 3
858#define DPIO_K_SHIFT (24) /* 4 bits */
859#define DPIO_P1_SHIFT (21) /* 3 bits */
860#define DPIO_P2_SHIFT (16) /* 5 bits */
861#define DPIO_N_SHIFT (12) /* 4 bits */
862#define DPIO_ENABLE_CALIBRATION (1<<11)

1448/*
1449 * Fence registers
1450 * [0-7] @ 0x2000 gen2,gen3
1451 * [8-15] @ 0x3000 945,g33,pnv
1452 *
1453 * [0-15] @ 0x3000 gen4,gen5
1454 *
1455 * [0-15] @ 0x100000 gen6,vlv,chv
1456 * [0-31] @ 0x100000 gen7+
1457 */
1458#define FENCE_REG(i) (0x2000 + (((i) & 8) << 9) + ((i) & 7) * 4)
1459#define I830_FENCE_START_MASK 0x07f80000
1460#define I830_FENCE_TILING_Y_SHIFT 12
1461#define I830_FENCE_SIZE_BITS(size) ((ffs((size) >> 19) - 1) << 8)
1462#define I830_FENCE_PITCH_SHIFT 4
1463#define I830_FENCE_REG_VALID (1<<0)
1464#define I915_FENCE_MAX_PITCH_VAL 4
1465#define I830_FENCE_MAX_PITCH_VAL 6
1466#define I830_FENCE_MAX_SIZE_VAL (1<<8)
1467
1468#define I915_FENCE_START_MASK 0x0ff00000
1469#define I915_FENCE_SIZE_BITS(size) ((ffs((size) >> 20) - 1) << 8)
1470
1471#define FENCE_REG_965_LO(i) (0x03000 + (i) * 8)
1472#define FENCE_REG_965_HI(i) (0x03000 + (i) * 8 + 4)
1473#define I965_FENCE_PITCH_SHIFT 2
1474#define I965_FENCE_TILING_Y_SHIFT 1
1475#define I965_FENCE_REG_VALID (1<<0)
1476#define I965_FENCE_MAX_PITCH_VAL 0x0400
1477
1478#define FENCE_REG_GEN6_LO(i) (0x100000 + (i) * 8)
1479#define FENCE_REG_GEN6_HI(i) (0x100000 + (i) * 8 + 4)

1937/* On modern GEN architectures interrupt control consists of two sets
1938 * of registers. The first set pertains to the ring generating the
1939 * interrupt. The second control is for the functional block generating the
1940 * interrupt. These are PM, GT, DE, etc.
1941 *
1942 * Luckily *knocks on wood* all the ring interrupt bits match up with the
1943 * GT interrupt bits, so we don't need to duplicate the defines.
1944 *
1945 * These defines should cover us well from SNB->HSW with minor exceptions
1946 * it can also work on ILK.
1947 */
1948#define GT_BLT_FLUSHDW_NOTIFY_INTERRUPT (1 << 26)
1949#define GT_BLT_CS_ERROR_INTERRUPT (1 << 25)
1950#define GT_BLT_USER_INTERRUPT (1 << 22)
1951#define GT_BSD_CS_ERROR_INTERRUPT (1 << 15)
1952#define GT_BSD_USER_INTERRUPT (1 << 12)
1953#define GT_RENDER_L3_PARITY_ERROR_INTERRUPT_S1 (1 << 11) /* hsw+; rsvd on snb, ivb, vlv */
1954#define GT_CONTEXT_SWITCH_INTERRUPT (1 << 8)
1955#define GT_RENDER_L3_PARITY_ERROR_INTERRUPT (1 << 5) /* !snb */
1956#define GT_RENDER_PIPECTL_NOTIFY_INTERRUPT (1 << 4)
1957#define GT_RENDER_CS_MASTER_ERROR_INTERRUPT (1 << 3)
1958#define GT_RENDER_SYNC_STATUS_INTERRUPT (1 << 2)
1959#define GT_RENDER_DEBUG_INTERRUPT (1 << 1)
1960#define GT_RENDER_USER_INTERRUPT (1 << 0)
1961
1962#define PM_VEBOX_CS_ERROR_INTERRUPT (1 << 12) /* hsw+ */
1963#define PM_VEBOX_USER_INTERRUPT (1 << 10) /* hsw+ */
1964
1965#define GT_PARITY_ERROR(dev) \
1966 (GT_RENDER_L3_PARITY_ERROR_INTERRUPT | \
1967 (IS_HASWELL(dev) ? GT_RENDER_L3_PARITY_ERROR_INTERRUPT_S1 : 0))
1968

2316/*
2317 * UDI pixel divider, controlling how many pixels are stuffed into a packet.
2318 *
2319 * Value is pixels minus 1. Must be set to 1 pixel for SDVO.
2320 */
2321#define DPLL_MD_UDI_DIVIDER_MASK 0x3f000000
2322#define DPLL_MD_UDI_DIVIDER_SHIFT 24
2323/* UDI pixel divider for VGA, same as DPLL_MD_UDI_DIVIDER_MASK. */
2324#define DPLL_MD_VGA_UDI_DIVIDER_MASK 0x003f0000
2325#define DPLL_MD_VGA_UDI_DIVIDER_SHIFT 16
2326/*
2327 * SDVO/UDI pixel multiplier.
2328 *
2329 * SDVO requires that the bus clock rate be between 1 and 2 Ghz, and the bus
2330 * clock rate is 10 times the DPLL clock. At low resolution/refresh rate
2331 * modes, the bus rate would be below the limits, so SDVO allows for stuffing
2332 * dummy bytes in the datastream at an increased clock rate, with both sides of
2333 * the link knowing how many bytes are fill.
2334 *
2335 * So, for a mode with a dotclock of 65Mhz, we would want to double the clock
2336 * rate to 130Mhz to get a bus rate of 1.30Ghz. The DPLL clock rate would be
2337 * set to 130Mhz, and the SDVO multiplier set to 2x in this register and
2338 * through an SDVO command.
2339 *
2340 * This register field has values of multiplication factor minus 1, with
2341 * a maximum multiplier of 5 for SDVO.
2342 */
2343#define DPLL_MD_UDI_MULTIPLIER_MASK 0x00003f00
2344#define DPLL_MD_UDI_MULTIPLIER_SHIFT 8
2345/*
2346 * SDVO/UDI pixel multiplier for VGA, same as DPLL_MD_UDI_MULTIPLIER_MASK.
2347 * This best be set to the default value (3) or the CRT won't work. No,
2348 * I don't entirely understand what this does...
2349 */
2350#define DPLL_MD_VGA_UDI_MULTIPLIER_MASK 0x0000003f
2351#define DPLL_MD_VGA_UDI_MULTIPLIER_SHIFT 0

2527/*
2528 * MCHBAR mirror.
2529 *
2530 * This mirrors the MCHBAR MMIO space whose location is determined by
2531 * device 0 function 0's pci config register 0x44 or 0x48 and matches it in
2532 * every way. It is not accessible from the CP register read instructions.
2533 *
2534 * Starting from Haswell, you can't write registers using the MCHBAR mirror,
2535 * just read.
2536 */

2852/*
2853 * Make these a multiple of magic 25 to avoid SNB (eg. Dell XPS
2854 * 8300) freezing up around GPU hangs. Looks as if even
2855 * scheduling/timer interrupts start misbehaving if the RPS
2856 * EI/thresholds are "bad", leading to a very sluggish or even
2857 * frozen machine.
2858 */
2859#define INTERVAL_1_28_US(us) roundup(((us) * 100) >> 7, 25)
2860#define INTERVAL_1_33_US(us) (((us) * 3) >> 2)
2861#define INTERVAL_0_833_US(us) (((us) * 6) / 5)
2862#define GT_INTERVAL_FROM_US(dev_priv, us) (IS_GEN9(dev_priv) ? \
2863 (IS_BROXTON(dev_priv) ? \
2864 INTERVAL_0_833_US(us) : \
2865 INTERVAL_1_33_US(us)) : \
2866 INTERVAL_1_28_US(us))
2867
2868/*
2869 * Logical Context regs
2870 */
2871#define CCID 0x2180
2872#define CCID_EN (1<<0)
2873/*
2874 * Notes on SNB/IVB/VLV context size:
2875 * - Power context is saved elsewhere (LLC or stolen)
2876 * - Ring/execlist context is saved on SNB, not on IVB
2877 * - Extended context size already includes render context size
2878 * - We always need to follow the extended context size.
2879 * SNB BSpec has comments indicating that we should use the
2880 * render context size instead if execlists are disabled, but
2881 * based on empirical testing that's just nonsense.
2882 * - Pipelined/VF state is saved on SNB/IVB respectively
2883 * - GT1 size just indicates how much of render context
2884 * doesn't need saving on GT1
2885 */
2886#define CXT_SIZE 0x21a0
2887#define GEN6_CXT_POWER_SIZE(cxt_reg) (((cxt_reg) >> 24) & 0x3f)
2888#define GEN6_CXT_RING_SIZE(cxt_reg) (((cxt_reg) >> 18) & 0x3f)
2889#define GEN6_CXT_RENDER_SIZE(cxt_reg) (((cxt_reg) >> 12) & 0x3f)
2890#define GEN6_CXT_EXTENDED_SIZE(cxt_reg) (((cxt_reg) >> 6) & 0x3f)
2891#define GEN6_CXT_PIPELINE_SIZE(cxt_reg) (((cxt_reg) >> 0) & 0x3f)
2892#define GEN6_CXT_TOTAL_SIZE(cxt_reg) (GEN6_CXT_RING_SIZE(cxt_reg) + \
2893 GEN6_CXT_EXTENDED_SIZE(cxt_reg) + \
2894 GEN6_CXT_PIPELINE_SIZE(cxt_reg))
2895#define GEN7_CXT_SIZE 0x21a8
2896#define GEN7_CXT_POWER_SIZE(ctx_reg) (((ctx_reg) >> 25) & 0x7f)
2897#define GEN7_CXT_RING_SIZE(ctx_reg) (((ctx_reg) >> 22) & 0x7)
2898#define GEN7_CXT_RENDER_SIZE(ctx_reg) (((ctx_reg) >> 16) & 0x3f)
2899#define GEN7_CXT_EXTENDED_SIZE(ctx_reg) (((ctx_reg) >> 9) & 0x7f)
2900#define GEN7_CXT_GT1_SIZE(ctx_reg) (((ctx_reg) >> 6) & 0x7)
2901#define GEN7_CXT_VFSTATE_SIZE(ctx_reg) (((ctx_reg) >> 0) & 0x3f)
2902#define GEN7_CXT_TOTAL_SIZE(ctx_reg) (GEN7_CXT_EXTENDED_SIZE(ctx_reg) + \
2903 GEN7_CXT_VFSTATE_SIZE(ctx_reg))
2904/* Haswell does have the CXT_SIZE register however it does not appear to be
2905 * valid. Now, docs explain in dwords what is in the context object. The full
2906 * size is 70720 bytes, however, the power context and execlist context will
2907 * never be saved (power context is stored elsewhere, and execlists don't work
2908 * on HSW) - so the final size, including the extra state required for the
2909 * Resource Streamer, is 66944 bytes, which rounds to 17 pages.
2910 */
2911#define HSW_CXT_TOTAL_SIZE (17 * PAGE_SIZE)
2912/* Same as Haswell, but 72064 bytes now. */
2913#define GEN8_CXT_TOTAL_SIZE (18 * PAGE_SIZE)

3253/*
3254 * HDMI/DP bits are g4x+
3255 *
3256 * WARNING: Bspec for hpd status bits on gen4 seems to be completely confused.
3257 * Please check the detailed lore in the commit message for for experimental
3258 * evidence.
3259 */
3260/* Bspec says GM45 should match G4X/VLV/CHV, but reality disagrees */
3261#define PORTD_HOTPLUG_LIVE_STATUS_GM45 (1 << 29)
3262#define PORTC_HOTPLUG_LIVE_STATUS_GM45 (1 << 28)
3263#define PORTB_HOTPLUG_LIVE_STATUS_GM45 (1 << 27)
3264/* G4X/VLV/CHV DP/HDMI bits again match Bspec */
3265#define PORTD_HOTPLUG_LIVE_STATUS_G4X (1 << 27)
3266#define PORTC_HOTPLUG_LIVE_STATUS_G4X (1 << 28)
3267#define PORTB_HOTPLUG_LIVE_STATUS_G4X (1 << 29)
3268#define PORTD_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS (3 << 21)
3269#define PORTD_HOTPLUG_INT_LONG_PULSE (2 << 21)
3270#define PORTD_HOTPLUG_INT_SHORT_PULSE (1 << 21)
3271#define PORTC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS (3 << 19)
3272#define PORTC_HOTPLUG_INT_LONG_PULSE (2 << 19)
3273#define PORTC_HOTPLUG_INT_SHORT_PULSE (1 << 19)
3274#define PORTB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS (3 << 17)
3275#define PORTB_HOTPLUG_INT_LONG_PULSE (2 << 17)
3276#define PORTB_HOTPLUG_INT_SHORT_PLUSE (1 << 17)
3277/* CRT/TV common between gen3+ */
3278#define CRT_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS (1 << 11)
3279#define TV_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS (1 << 10)
3280#define CRT_HOTPLUG_MONITOR_MASK (3 << 8)
3281#define CRT_HOTPLUG_MONITOR_COLOR (3 << 8)
3282#define CRT_HOTPLUG_MONITOR_MONO (2 << 8)
3283#define CRT_HOTPLUG_MONITOR_NONE (0 << 8)
3284#define DP_AUX_CHANNEL_D_INT_STATUS_G4X (1 << 6)
3285#define DP_AUX_CHANNEL_C_INT_STATUS_G4X (1 << 5)
3286#define DP_AUX_CHANNEL_B_INT_STATUS_G4X (1 << 4)
3287#define DP_AUX_CHANNEL_MASK_INT_STATUS_G4X (7 << 4)
3288
3289/* SDVO is different across gen3/4 */
3290#define SDVOC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_G4X (1 << 3)
3291#define SDVOB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_G4X (1 << 2)
3292/*
3293 * Bspec seems to be seriously misleaded about the SDVO hpd bits on i965g/gm,
3294 * since reality corrobates that they're the same as on gen3. But keep these
3295 * bits here (and the comment!) to help any other lost wanderers back onto the
3296 * right tracks.
3297 */
3298#define SDVOC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I965 (3 << 4)
3299#define SDVOB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I965 (3 << 2)
3300#define SDVOC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I915 (1 << 7)
3301#define SDVOB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I915 (1 << 6)
3302#define HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_G4X (CRT_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS | \
3303 SDVOB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_G4X | \
3304 SDVOC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_G4X | \
3305 PORTB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS | \
3306 PORTC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS | \
3307 PORTD_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS)
3308
3309#define HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I915 (CRT_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS | \
3310 SDVOB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I915 | \
3311 SDVOC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS_I915 | \
3312 PORTB_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS | \
3313 PORTC_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS | \
3314 PORTD_HOTPLUG_INT_STATUS)

3425/* LVDS port control */
3426#define LVDS 0x61180
3427/*
3428 * Enables the LVDS port. This bit must be set before DPLLs are enabled, as
3429 * the DPLL semantics change when the LVDS is assigned to that pipe.
3430 */
3431#define LVDS_PORT_EN (1 << 31)
3432/* Selects pipe B for LVDS data. Must be set on pre-965. */
3433#define LVDS_PIPEB_SELECT (1 << 30)
3434#define LVDS_PIPE_MASK (1 << 30)
3435#define LVDS_PIPE(pipe) ((pipe) << 30)
3436/* LVDS dithering flag on 965/g4x platform */
3437#define LVDS_ENABLE_DITHER (1 << 25)
3438/* LVDS sync polarity flags. Set to invert (i.e. negative) */
3439#define LVDS_VSYNC_POLARITY (1 << 21)
3440#define LVDS_HSYNC_POLARITY (1 << 20)
3441
3442/* Enable border for unscaled (or aspect-scaled) display */
3443#define LVDS_BORDER_ENABLE (1 << 15)
3444/*
3445 * Enables the A0-A2 data pairs and CLKA, containing 18 bits of color data per
3446 * pixel.
3447 */
3448#define LVDS_A0A2_CLKA_POWER_MASK (3 << 8)
3449#define LVDS_A0A2_CLKA_POWER_DOWN (0 << 8)
3450#define LVDS_A0A2_CLKA_POWER_UP (3 << 8)
3451/*
3452 * Controls the A3 data pair, which contains the additional LSBs for 24 bit
3453 * mode. Only enabled if LVDS_A0A2_CLKA_POWER_UP also indicates it should be
3454 * on.
3455 */
3456#define LVDS_A3_POWER_MASK (3 << 6)
3457#define LVDS_A3_POWER_DOWN (0 << 6)
3458#define LVDS_A3_POWER_UP (3 << 6)
3459/*
3460 * Controls the CLKB pair. This should only be set when LVDS_B0B3_POWER_UP
3461 * is set.
3462 */
3463#define LVDS_CLKB_POWER_MASK (3 << 4)
3464#define LVDS_CLKB_POWER_DOWN (0 << 4)
3465#define LVDS_CLKB_POWER_UP (3 << 4)
3466/*
3467 * Controls the B0-B3 data pairs. This must be set to match the DPLL p2
3468 * setting for whether we are in dual-channel mode. The B3 pair will
3469 * additionally only be powered up when LVDS_A3_POWER_UP is set.
3470 */
3471#define LVDS_B0B3_POWER_MASK (3 << 2)
3472#define LVDS_B0B3_POWER_DOWN (0 << 2)
3473#define LVDS_B0B3_POWER_UP (3 << 2)
3474

3478 * (Haswell and newer) to see which VIDEO_DIP_DATA byte corresponds to each byte
3479 * of the infoframe structure specified by CEA-861. */
3480#define VIDEO_DIP_DATA_SIZE 32
3481#define VIDEO_DIP_VSC_DATA_SIZE 36

3490#define VIDEO_DIP_ENABLE_GAMUT (4 << 21)

3499#define VIDEO_DIP_FREQ_MASK (3 << 16)
3500/* HSW and later: */
3501#define VIDEO_DIP_ENABLE_VSC_HSW (1 << 20)
3502#define VIDEO_DIP_ENABLE_GCP_HSW (1 << 16)

3683/* TV port control */

3692# define TV_ENC_OUTPUT_SVIDEO (1 << 28)
3693/* Outputs Component video (DAC A/B/C) */
3694# define TV_ENC_OUTPUT_COMPONENT (2 << 28)

3703# define TV_OVERSAMPLE_2X (1 << 18)

3705# define TV_OVERSAMPLE_NONE (2 << 18)

3707# define TV_OVERSAMPLE_8X (3 << 18)

3711# define TV_PAL_BURST (1 << 16)

3713# define TV_YC_SKEW_MASK (7 << 12)

3719 * Not sure what it does.

3728# define TV_FUSE_STATE_NO_MACROVISION (1 << 4)

3730# define TV_FUSE_STATE_DISABLED (2 << 4)

3736# define TV_TEST_MODE_PATTERN_2 (2 << 0)

3738# define TV_TEST_MODE_PATTERN_3 (3 << 0)

3740# define TV_TEST_MODE_PATTERN_4 (4 << 0)

3796/*
3797 * CSC coefficients are stored in a floating point format with 9 bits of
3798 * mantissa and 2 or 3 bits of exponent. The exponent is represented as 2**-n,
3799 * where 2-bit exponents are unsigned n, and 3-bit exponents are signed n with
3800 * -1 (0x3) being the only legal negative value.
3801 */

4309
4310/*
4311 * Computing GMCH M and N values for the Display Port link
4312 *
4313 * GMCH M/N = dot clock * bytes per pixel / ls_clk * # of lanes
4314 *
4315 * ls_clk (we assume) is the DP link clock (1.62 or 2.7 GHz)
4316 *
4317 * The GMCH value is used internally
4318 *
4319 * bytes_per_pixel is the number of bytes coming out of the plane,
4320 * which is after the LUTs, so we want the bytes for our color format.
4321 * For our current usage, this is always 3, one byte for R, G and B.
4322 */
4323#define _PIPEA_DATA_M_G4X 0x70050
4324#define _PIPEB_DATA_M_G4X 0x71050
4325
4326/* Transfer unit size for display port - 1, default is 0x3f (for TU size 64) */
4327#define TU_SIZE(x) (((x)-1) << 25) /* default size 64 */
4328#define TU_SIZE_SHIFT 25
4329#define TU_SIZE_MASK (0x3f << 25)
4330
4331#define DATA_LINK_M_N_MASK (0xffffff)
4332#define DATA_LINK_N_MAX (0x800000)
4333
4334#define _PIPEA_DATA_N_G4X 0x70054
4335#define _PIPEB_DATA_N_G4X 0x71054
4336#define PIPE_GMCH_DATA_N_MASK (0xffffff)
4337
4338/*
4339 * Computing Link M and N values for the Display Port link
4340 *
4341 * Link M / N = pixel_clock / ls_clk
4342 *
4343 * (the DP spec calls pixel_clock the 'strm_clk')
4344 *
4345 * The Link value is transmitted in the Main Stream
4346 * Attributes and VB-ID.
4347 */
4348
4349#define _PIPEA_LINK_M_G4X 0x70060
4350#define _PIPEB_LINK_M_G4X 0x71060
4351#define PIPEA_DP_LINK_M_MASK (0xffffff)
4352
4353#define _PIPEA_LINK_N_G4X 0x70064
4354#define _PIPEB_LINK_N_G4X 0x71064
4355#define PIPEA_DP_LINK_N_MASK (0xffffff)
4356
4357#define PIPE_DATA_M_G4X(pipe) _PIPE(pipe, _PIPEA_DATA_M_G4X, _PIPEB_DATA_M_G4X)
4358#define PIPE_DATA_N_G4X(pipe) _PIPE(pipe, _PIPEA_DATA_N_G4X, _PIPEB_DATA_N_G4X)
4359#define PIPE_LINK_M_G4X(pipe) _PIPE(pipe, _PIPEA_LINK_M_G4X, _PIPEB_LINK_M_G4X)
4360#define PIPE_LINK_N_G4X(pipe) _PIPE(pipe, _PIPEA_LINK_N_G4X, _PIPEB_LINK_N_G4X)

4844/*
4845 * The two pipe frame counter registers are not synchronized, so
4846 * reading a stable value is somewhat tricky. The following code
4847 * should work:
4848 *
4849 * do {
4850 * high1 = ((INREG(PIPEAFRAMEHIGH) & PIPE_FRAME_HIGH_MASK) >>
4851 * PIPE_FRAME_HIGH_SHIFT;
4852 * low1 = ((INREG(PIPEAFRAMEPIXEL) & PIPE_FRAME_LOW_MASK) >>
4853 * PIPE_FRAME_LOW_SHIFT);
4854 * high2 = ((INREG(PIPEAFRAMEHIGH) & PIPE_FRAME_HIGH_MASK) >>
4855 * PIPE_FRAME_HIGH_SHIFT);
4856 * } while (high1 != high2);
4857 * frame = (high1 << 8) | low1;
4858 */
4859#define _PIPEAFRAMEHIGH 0x70040
4860#define PIPE_FRAME_HIGH_MASK 0x0000ffff
4861#define PIPE_FRAME_HIGH_SHIFT 0
4862#define _PIPEAFRAMEPIXEL 0x70044
4863#define PIPE_FRAME_LOW_MASK 0xff000000
4864#define PIPE_FRAME_LOW_SHIFT 24
4865#define PIPE_PIXEL_MASK 0x00ffffff
4866#define PIPE_PIXEL_SHIFT 0
4867/* GM45+ just has to be different */
4868#define _PIPEA_FRMCOUNT_G4X 0x70040
4869#define _PIPEA_FLIPCOUNT_G4X 0x70044
4870#define PIPE_FRMCOUNT_G4X(pipe) _PIPE2(pipe, _PIPEA_FRMCOUNT_G4X)
4871#define PIPE_FLIPCOUNT_G4X(pipe) _PIPE2(pipe, _PIPEA_FLIPCOUNT_G4X)
4872

5258/*
5259 * CHV pipe B sprite CSC
5260 *
5261 * |cr| |c0 c1 c2| |cr + cr_ioff| |cr_ooff|
5262 * |yg| = |c3 c4 c5| x |yg + yg_ioff| + |yg_ooff|
5263 * |cb| |c6 c7 c8| |cb + cr_ioff| |cb_ooff|
5264 */
5265#define SPCSCYGOFF(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d900 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5266#define SPCSCCBOFF(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d904 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5267#define SPCSCCROFF(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d908 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5268#define SPCSC_OOFF(x) (((x) & 0x7ff) << 16) /* s11 */
5269#define SPCSC_IOFF(x) (((x) & 0x7ff) << 0) /* s11 */
5270
5271#define SPCSCC01(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d90c + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5272#define SPCSCC23(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d910 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5273#define SPCSCC45(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d914 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5274#define SPCSCC67(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d918 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5275#define SPCSCC8(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d91c + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5276#define SPCSC_C1(x) (((x) & 0x7fff) << 16) /* s3.12 */
5277#define SPCSC_C0(x) (((x) & 0x7fff) << 0) /* s3.12 */
5278
5279#define SPCSCYGICLAMP(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d920 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5280#define SPCSCCBICLAMP(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d924 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5281#define SPCSCCRICLAMP(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d928 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5282#define SPCSC_IMAX(x) (((x) & 0x7ff) << 16) /* s11 */
5283#define SPCSC_IMIN(x) (((x) & 0x7ff) << 0) /* s11 */
5284
5285#define SPCSCYGOCLAMP(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d92c + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5286#define SPCSCCBOCLAMP(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d930 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5287#define SPCSCCROCLAMP(sprite) (VLV_DISPLAY_BASE + 0x6d934 + (sprite) * 0x1000)
5288#define SPCSC_OMAX(x) ((x) << 16) /* u10 */
5289#define SPCSC_OMIN(x) ((x) << 0) /* u10 */

7595/* BXT MIPI clock controls */
7596#define BXT_MAX_VAR_OUTPUT_KHZ 39500
7597
7598#define BXT_MIPI_CLOCK_CTL 0x46090
7599#define BXT_MIPI1_DIV_SHIFT 26
7600#define BXT_MIPI2_DIV_SHIFT 10
7601#define BXT_MIPI_DIV_SHIFT(port) \
7602 _MIPI_PORT(port, BXT_MIPI1_DIV_SHIFT, \
7603 BXT_MIPI2_DIV_SHIFT)
7604/* Var clock divider to generate TX source. Result must be < 39.5 M */
7605#define BXT_MIPI1_ESCLK_VAR_DIV_MASK (0x3F << 26)
7606#define BXT_MIPI2_ESCLK_VAR_DIV_MASK (0x3F << 10)
7607#define BXT_MIPI_ESCLK_VAR_DIV_MASK(port) \
7608 _MIPI_PORT(port, BXT_MIPI1_ESCLK_VAR_DIV_MASK, \
7609 BXT_MIPI2_ESCLK_VAR_DIV_MASK)
7610
7611#define BXT_MIPI_ESCLK_VAR_DIV(port, val) \
7612 (val << BXT_MIPI_DIV_SHIFT(port))
7613/* TX control divider to select actual TX clock output from (8x/var) */
7614#define BXT_MIPI1_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT 21
7615#define BXT_MIPI2_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT 5
7616#define BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port) \
7617 _MIPI_PORT(port, BXT_MIPI1_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT, \
7618 BXT_MIPI2_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT)
7619#define BXT_MIPI1_TX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK (3 << 21)
7620#define BXT_MIPI2_TX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK (3 << 5)
7621#define BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK(port) \
7622 _MIPI_PORT(port, BXT_MIPI1_TX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK, \
7623 BXT_MIPI2_TX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK)
7624#define BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_8XDIV_BY2(port) \
7625 (0x0 << BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7626#define BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_8XDIV_BY4(port) \
7627 (0x1 << BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7628#define BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_8XDIV_BY8(port) \
7629 (0x2 << BXT_MIPI_TX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7630/* RX control divider to select actual RX clock output from 8x*/
7631#define BXT_MIPI1_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT 19
7632#define BXT_MIPI2_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT 3
7633#define BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port) \
7634 _MIPI_PORT(port, BXT_MIPI1_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT, \
7635 BXT_MIPI2_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT)
7636#define BXT_MIPI1_RX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK (3 << 19)
7637#define BXT_MIPI2_RX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK (3 << 3)
7638#define BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_FIXDIV_MASK(port) \
7639 (3 << BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7640#define BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_8X_BY2(port) \
7641 (1 << BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7642#define BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_8X_BY3(port) \
7643 (2 << BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7644#define BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_8X_BY4(port) \
7645 (3 << BXT_MIPI_RX_ESCLK_SHIFT(port))
7646/* BXT-A WA: Always prog DPHY dividers to 00 */
7647#define BXT_MIPI1_DPHY_DIV_SHIFT 16
7648#define BXT_MIPI2_DPHY_DIV_SHIFT 0
7649#define BXT_MIPI_DPHY_DIV_SHIFT(port) \
7650 _MIPI_PORT(port, BXT_MIPI1_DPHY_DIV_SHIFT, \
7651 BXT_MIPI2_DPHY_DIV_SHIFT)
7652#define BXT_MIPI_1_DPHY_DIVIDER_MASK (3 << 16)
7653#define BXT_MIPI_2_DPHY_DIVIDER_MASK (3 << 0)

8102#define MIPI_CTRL(port) _MIPI_PORT(port, _MIPIA_CTRL, \
8103 _MIPIC_CTRL)
8104#define ESCAPE_CLOCK_DIVIDER_SHIFT 5 /* A only */
8105#define ESCAPE_CLOCK_DIVIDER_MASK (3 << 5)
8106#define ESCAPE_CLOCK_DIVIDER_1 (0 << 5)
8107#define ESCAPE_CLOCK_DIVIDER_2 (1 << 5)
8108#define ESCAPE_CLOCK_DIVIDER_4 (2 << 5)
8109#define READ_REQUEST_PRIORITY_SHIFT 3
8110#define READ_REQUEST_PRIORITY_MASK (3 << 3)
8111#define READ_REQUEST_PRIORITY_LOW (0 << 3)
8112#define READ_REQUEST_PRIORITY_HIGH (3 << 3)
8113#define RGB_FLIP_TO_BGR (1 << 2)
8114
8115#define BXT_PIPE_SELECT_MASK (7 << 7)
8116#define BXT_PIPE_SELECT_C (2 << 7)
8117#define BXT_PIPE_SELECT_B (1 << 7)
8118#define BXT_PIPE_SELECT_A (0 << 7)
8119
8120#define _MIPIA_DATA_ADDRESS (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb108)
8121#define _MIPIC_DATA_ADDRESS (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb908)
8122#define MIPI_DATA_ADDRESS(port) _MIPI_PORT(port, _MIPIA_DATA_ADDRESS, \
8123 _MIPIC_DATA_ADDRESS)
8124#define DATA_MEM_ADDRESS_SHIFT 5
8125#define DATA_MEM_ADDRESS_MASK (0x7ffffff << 5)
8126#define DATA_VALID (1 << 0)
8127
8128#define _MIPIA_DATA_LENGTH (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb10c)
8129#define _MIPIC_DATA_LENGTH (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb90c)
8130#define MIPI_DATA_LENGTH(port) _MIPI_PORT(port, _MIPIA_DATA_LENGTH, \
8131 _MIPIC_DATA_LENGTH)
8132#define DATA_LENGTH_SHIFT 0
8133#define DATA_LENGTH_MASK (0xfffff << 0)
8134
8135#define _MIPIA_COMMAND_ADDRESS (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb110)
8136#define _MIPIC_COMMAND_ADDRESS (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb910)
8137#define MIPI_COMMAND_ADDRESS(port) _MIPI_PORT(port, \
8138 _MIPIA_COMMAND_ADDRESS, _MIPIC_COMMAND_ADDRESS)
8139#define COMMAND_MEM_ADDRESS_SHIFT 5
8140#define COMMAND_MEM_ADDRESS_MASK (0x7ffffff << 5)
8141#define AUTO_PWG_ENABLE (1 << 2)
8142#define MEMORY_WRITE_DATA_FROM_PIPE_RENDERING (1 << 1)
8143#define COMMAND_VALID (1 << 0)
8144
8145#define _MIPIA_COMMAND_LENGTH (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb114)
8146#define _MIPIC_COMMAND_LENGTH (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb914)
8147#define MIPI_COMMAND_LENGTH(port) _MIPI_PORT(port, _MIPIA_COMMAND_LENGTH, \
8148 _MIPIC_COMMAND_LENGTH)
8149#define COMMAND_LENGTH_SHIFT(n) (8 * (n)) /* n: 0...3 */
8150#define COMMAND_LENGTH_MASK(n) (0xff << (8 * (n)))
8151
8152#define _MIPIA_READ_DATA_RETURN0 (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb118)
8153#define _MIPIC_READ_DATA_RETURN0 (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb918)
8154#define MIPI_READ_DATA_RETURN(port, n) \
8155 (_MIPI_PORT(port, _MIPIA_READ_DATA_RETURN0, _MIPIC_READ_DATA_RETURN0) \
8156 + 4 * (n)) /* n: 0...7 */
8157

8159#define _MIPIC_READ_DATA_VALID (dev_priv->mipi_mmio_base + 0xb938)

8162#define READ_DATA_VALID(n) (1 << (n))
